prev was an Integer, which is immutable.

In Java, primitive values (and wrappers like Integer) are passed by value.
When you do prev = root.val; inside recursion, you’re only reassigning the local copy.
The caller’s prev never changes.
→ ❌ That’s why recursion “loses” the updated state unless you:
Make prev a class variable (shared across all calls), or
Wrap it in a mutable holder (like AtomicInteger[] prev = new AtomicInteger[1]), or
Return it explicitly through recursion

